&lt;/div&gt;&lt;img src="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~r/lifehacker/vip/~4/6j6cRwBL_4U" height="1" width="1"&gt;</summary><author><name>Adam Dachis</name></author><gr:likingUser>15835440548890645348</gr:likingUser><gr:likingUser>17252568258677848776</gr:likingUser><gr:likingUser>05703684006140538891</gr:likingUser><gr:likingUser>04143453733828550875</gr:likingUser><gr:likingUser>12887533931206668684</gr:likingUser><gr:likingUser>11516725439115563238</gr:likingUser><gr:likingUser>01169483390620181922</gr:likingUser><gr:likingUser>01344894172095296252</gr:likingUser><gr:likingUser>07083586920809426844</gr:likingUser><gr:likingUser>17344907245931675820</gr:likingUser><gr:likingUser>01549285130410986369</gr:likingUser><gr:likingUser>03897606480101923556</gr:likingUser><gr:likingUser>00584827447919255880</gr:likingUser><gr:likingUser>04301764884822384276</gr:likingUser><gr:likingUser>01933282990689691726</gr:likingUser><gr:likingUser>02138826466712097385</gr:likingUser><gr:likingUser>12038536455554650851</gr:likingUser><gr:likingUser>00333148508474029279</gr:likingUser><gr:likingUser>00194659170755847141</gr:likingUser><gr:likingUser>02142804759097738512</gr:likingUser><source gr:stream-id="feed/http://feeds.gawker.com/lifehacker/vip"><id>tag:google.com,2005:reader/feed/http://feeds.gawker.com/lifehacker/vip</id><title type="html">Lifehacker</title><link rel="alternate" href="http://lifehacker.com" type="text/html"/></source></entry><entry gr:crawl-timestamp-msec="1305917189662"><id gr:original-id="http://www.giantsfootballblog.com/?p=20918">tag:google.com,2005:reader/item/778b3f28aac1a0d7</id><category term="New York City"/><category term="New York Giants"/><category term="New York Giants News"/><category term="Tyler Sash"/><category term="Iowa Hawkeyes"/><category term="New York Giants Blogs"/><title type="html">Did Giants Get Late Round Steal in Tyler Sash?</title><published>2011-05-07T17:03:31Z</published><updated>2011-05-07T17:03:31Z</updated><link rel="alternate" href="http://www.giantsfootballblog.com/2011/05/07/did-giants-get-late-round-steal-in-tyler-sash/" type="text/html"/><content xml:base="http://www.giantsfootballblog.com/" type="html">&lt;p&gt;I wasn’t so sure about this Tyler Sash, the safety the Giants drafted in the 6th round out of Iowa last weekend.  Then, I did some research.  By all accounts, and what I have seen, this guy can play the game of&lt;a href="http://www.giantsfootballblog.com/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/2011/05/SASH.jpg"&gt;&lt;img title="Orange Bowl - Iowa v Georgia Tech" src="http://www.giantsfootballblog.com/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/2011/05/SASH.jpg" alt="" width="150" height="200"&gt;&lt;/a&gt; football.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Sash is the type of player the Giants need in their secondary and on special teams: heady, tough and motivated.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The passages below are from the Iowa Football blog &lt;strong&gt;Black Heart, Gold Pants…..&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="color:#800000"&gt;&lt;em&gt;He was the most decorated safety at Iowa since Bob Sanders roamed the secondary and instilled fear in Big Ten receivers…Like most multi-year starters at safety at Iowa, Sash was a well-rounded player, adept at both shutting down the run and putting the clamps down on passing attacks.  But of those two, he was better against the pass; Sash had an uncanny ability to be in the right place at the right time to knock down passes or to pluck an errant pass out of the air and go racing downfield with it.  He also seemed to have an amazing knack at making big plays at big moments…&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="color:#800000"&gt;&lt;em&gt;For much of his Iowa career, he had an incredible ability to be exactly where he needed to be in order to make big plays; it can’t all have been sheer coincidence or pure luck.  Aside from his near-magical big play abilities, Sash also possessed good coverage skills (he was rarely beaten deep or the source of broken coverages that gave up big pass plays), and was solid against the run…..It doesn’t hurt Sash’s case that Iowa has put a slew of safeties into the NFL under Kirk Ferentz — Derek Pagel, Sean Considine, and Bob Sanders all had (or continue to have) multi-year NFL careers and even Marcus Paschal hung around the NFL for quite a while….&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;These elements did not get past the Giants. They used their first of two compensatory selections in Round Six to grab Sash.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="color:#003366"&gt;&lt;em&gt;“This guy has good size, he runs good enough,&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/span&gt;” said Marc Ross, the Giants’ director of college scouting. &lt;em&gt;&lt;span style="color:#003366"&gt;“He is not your top-flight athlete, but the guy has a feel for the game — instinctive, excellent ball skills….We hope he will play special teams for us. He has that kind of toughness about him, reckless with his body. So we really like that about him.”&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;In addition to being a folk legend in Iowa, Sash is fully cognizant of his roots and is active in giving back to the community.  Last week, Sash helped raise $22k to help a local cancer patient……&lt;strong&gt;&lt;a href="http://www.kcci.com/video/27566428/detail.html"&gt;WATCH&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
</content><author><name>John Fennelly</name></author><source gr:stream-id="feed/http://www.giantsfootballblog.com/feed/"><id>tag:google.com,2005:reader/feed/http://www.giantsfootballblog.com/feed/</id><title type="html">GiantsFootballBlog.com</title><link rel="alternate" href="http://www.giantsfootballblog.com" type="text/html"/></source></entry><entry gr:crawl-timestamp-msec="1305917184084"><id gr:original-id="Lifehacker-5799690">tag:google.com,2005:reader/item/0103904d46177cff</id><category term="Business Cards"/><category term="about.me"/><category term="Free"/><category term="Networking"/><category term="offer"/><category term="Self-Promotion"/><title type="html">About.me Business Cards are a Free Way to Promote Yourself [Business Cards]</title><published>2011-05-08T20:00:00Z</published><updated>2011-05-08T20:00:00Z</updated><link rel="alternate" href="http://feeds.gawker.com/~r/lifehacker/vip/~3/ZoCyzrIiPDs/aboutme-business-cards-are-a-free-way-to-promote-yourself" type="text/html"/><summary xml:base="http://lifehacker.com/" type="html">&lt;p&gt;&lt;a rel="lytebox" href="http://cache.gawkerassets.com/assets/images/17/2011/05/about-me-card.jpg"&gt;&lt;img src="http://cache.gawkerassets.com/assets/images/17/2011/05/500x_about-me-card.jpg" width="500" alt="About.me Business Cards are a Free Way to Promote Yourself" title="About.me Business Cards are a Free Way to Promote Yourself"&gt;&lt;/a&gt; A personal business card doesn't have to come from the company you work for. Sometimes, you want a business card that's about you, not the company that employs you. Thankfully, About.me, &lt;a href="http://lifehacker.com/#!5714529/aboutme-creates-a-personal-landing-page-in-dead-simple-steps"&gt;one of our favorite personal landing page services&lt;/a&gt;, is willing to send you some. You just pay shipping.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;In some cases, a personal business card is exactly what you need. It can tell a new acquaintance, client, or potential employer about you personally, and give them a way to reach you that's not routed through your office phone or your corporate e-mail account, and if you're a happy office worker that does freelance work on the side, having different business cards for different encounters can be a lifesaver.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;To that end, About.me and Moo, a Web-based custom printing company, have partnered up to let About.me users design business cards based on their profiles. The new cards have your profile image on the front, and on the back they feature your name, your About.me profile URL and e-mail address (if you choose,) and a QR code. The people you give your card to can scan the QR code to visit your About.me profile right there on their phone.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;You can customize the card to include a headline, a phone number, or any other information you want that's not normally included. Since the cards are free, there's a Moo logo on the bottom, but you can have it removed if you pay a premium.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;One of About.me's goals is to give people a Web-based business card they can point anyone to. The business cards are a natural extension of the idea, and it doesn't hurt that they're willing to print 50 of them for free and send them to you – as long as you pay $5.50 shipping. If you don't have an About.me landing page, you can sign up for free to take advantage of the offer.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src="http://cache.gawker.com/assets/images/lifehacker/2011/02/style-attribution-arrow-2.png" title="About.me Business Cards are a Free Way to Promote Yourself" alt="About.me Business Cards are a Free Way to Promote Yourself" height="20" width="19"&gt; &lt;a href="http://about.me/offers/cards"&gt;About.me Business Cards&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;hr&gt;
